        ECMAScript 2015 (ES6) Classes
        The new <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Classes" target="_blank">Class keyword</a> in EcmaScript 2015 (former name ES6) is nothing but more confusion for programmers.<br />It is just a syntactical sugar over the existing <a href="http://javascript.info/tutorial/all-one-constructor-pattern"> Javascript's constructor pattern</a> for creating objects, which is already a great confusion for Javascript developers.<!--more--><br /> JavaScript is not a classical Class/Object language, and its OOP doesn't share the same paradigm.<br /> <h3>How JavaScript OOP is different? </h3>OOP in JavaScript is prototypal based, which means there is only objects in JavaScript, and inheritance means objects inherits from existing objects. <br />But when JavaScript was designed, most of developers know OOP as class/object, and JavaScript creator wanted to sell the language to the wide development team, so he introduced the constructor pattern with the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/new" target="_blank">"new" operator</a>.<br /><h3>What the prototypal-way to create an object?</h3>The prototypal-way of creating new objects is by just using object literal, and to inherit from existing object is to use the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/create">Object.create</a> which was introduced in EcmaScript 5. <br/> as an example:  
<pre class="line-numbers"><code class="language-javascript">var animal = {
    name: 'animal',
    sound: function() {
        console.log('animal sound');
    }
);

var cat = Object.create(animal);
cat.sound = function() {
    console.log('cat sound');
};</code></pre> 
